1. The API Wrapper (Auth & Retry)
	• Situation: Teams were manually handling headers, OAuth2/Keycloak tokens, and failing tests due to intermittent network glitches (503/504 errors).
	• Task: Standardize API interactions to ensure consistency and eliminate "flaky" test failures.
	• Action: I built EBAuthClient by extending requests.Session. I implemented automatic token injection and used an HTTPAdapter with urllib3.Retry to handle transient network errors.
	• Result: Reduced "flaky" test noise by over 50% and saved every developer from writing manual retry/auth logic.


# How I built it:
from requests.adapters import HTTPAdapter
from urllib3.util import Retry

class EBAuthClient(requests.Session):
    def __init__(self, token):
        super().__init__()
        self.headers.update({"Authorization": f"Bearer {token}"})
        # Retry mechanism for flaky APIs
        adapter = HTTPAdapter(max_retries=Retry(total=3, status_forcelist=[503, 504]))
        self.mount("https://", adapter)


2. The JSON & Schema Validator
	• Situation: Dealing with massive, nested API responses was error-prone, and developers were writing fragile, repetitive assertions for every single field.
	• Task: Create a robust way to extract data and validate the structure without writing 50+ lines of assert statements.
	• Action: I used jsonpath_ng for deep data extraction and jsonschema to validate entire API responses against a predefined structure in one go.
	• Result: Simplified test maintenance; updating a field now only requires a quick schema change instead of rewriting dozens of individual test cases


# How I built it:
from jsonschema import validate
from jsonpath_ng import parse

def validate_response(data, schema):
    validate(instance=data, schema=schema) # Full structure validation

def get_data(data, path):
    return [match.value for match in parse(path).find(data)] # Deep extraction


3. The Soft Assertion Library
	• Situation: Tests were failing at the first error, which meant developers spent hours rerunning tests just to find the "next" bug in the same response.
	• Task: Enable comprehensive reporting where a single test execution validates multiple fields and reports all failures at once.
	• Action: I built a SoftAssert wrapper that collects failures in a list and only raises a final exception at the end of the test.
	• Result: Significantly faster debugging; developers now see a full list of everything that's broken in one report, turning "rerun loops" into "fix-it sessions."

# How I built it:
class SoftAssert:
    def __init__(self): self.errors = []
    def verify(self, condition, msg):
        if not condition: self.errors.append(msg)
    def assert_all(self):
        if self.errors: raise AssertionError(f"Failures: {'; '.join(self.errors)}")

4. Data Reporter
	• Situation: Every team was formatting their test results differently, which made it impossible for leadership or other teams to track overall product quality across our various microservices.
	• Task: Create a centralized, standardized reporting mechanism that would automatically aggregate test outcomes into a single, accessible dashboard.
	• Action: I built a shared Reporting Library using Pytest hooks (pytest_runtest_makereport). Instead of outputting raw text, every test execution now triggers a standardized Result object (a Python dataclass) that captures the test name, execution time, error stack traces, and environment details. This is then pushed to a central API that populates our Allure/Grafana dashboards.
	• Result: We achieved 100% visibility into test health. Stakeholders can now view pass/fail trends, flakiness metrics, and performance regressions across all projects in real-time, which completely eliminated the need for manual status reporting.

import pytest
import requests

# The Reporting Library implementation
class Reporter:
    @staticmethod
    def send_report(report_data):
        # Pushes test results to a centralized dashboard API
        requests.post("https://dashboard.internal.api/ingest", json=report_data)

# How it hooks into the test suite (e.g., conftest.py)
@pytest.hookimpl(tryfirst=True, hookwrapper=True)
def pytest_runtest_makereport(item, call):
    outcome = yield
    report = outcome.get_result()
    if report.when == "call":
        result_data = {
            "test_name": item.name,
            "status": "passed" if report.passed else "failed",
            "duration": report.duration
        }

        Reporter.send_report(result_data)

5. The Centralized Auth Library (Factory Pattern)
	• Situation: Managing authentication across different microservices was becoming a maintenance nightmare. Every service was implementing its own logic for Basic Auth, Keycloak, or JWT validation, which led to a lot of code duplication and inconsistent security.
	• Task: Centralize auth handling so every service uses the same interface regardless of the protocol.
	• Action: I built a Centralized Auth Library based on the Factory Pattern.

The Architecture

The Interface: I defined an abstract BaseAuth class that enforced standard methods like authenticate(), get_headers(), and refresh_token(). This ensured that no matter what auth method we used, the interface remained consistent for the developer.

The Concrete Implementations: I wrote separate classes for each type — BasicAuth, KeycloakAuth, and JWTAuth. Each class handled the specific handshake, credential validation, and token-handling logic for that protocol.

The Factory: I created an AuthFactory as the single entry point. The user simply passes the auth_type (like 'keycloak') and the required credentials (client ID/secret) to the factory, and it returns a pre-configured object ready for use.

from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

# 1. The Contract: Define what every Auth method must do
class BaseAuth(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def get_auth_headers(self):
        pass

# 2. Concrete Implementations
class BasicAuth(BaseAuth):
    def __init__(self, username, password):
        self.creds = (username, password)

    def get_auth_headers(self):
        return {"Authorization": "Basic ..."}

class KeycloakAuth(BaseAuth):
    def __init__(self, client_id, secret):
        self.client_id = client_id
        self.secret = secret

    def get_auth_headers(self):
        # Logic to fetch/refresh Keycloak token
        return {"Authorization": "Bearer <keycloak_token>"}

class JWTAuth(BaseAuth):
    def __init__(self, token):
        self.token = token

    def get_auth_headers(self):
        return {"Authorization": f"Bearer {self.token}"}

# 3. The Factory: The single entry point for the user
class AuthFactory:
    _mapping = {
        "basic": BasicAuth,
        "keycloak": KeycloakAuth,
        "jwt": JWTAuth
    }

    @staticmethod
    def get_auth(auth_type, **kwargs):
        auth_class = AuthFactory._mapping.get(auth_type.lower())
        if not auth_class:
            raise ValueError(f"Auth type '{auth_type}' not supported.")
        return auth_class(**kwargs)


# To use Keycloak:
auth_client = AuthFactory.get_auth("keycloak", client_id="my_id", secret="my_secret")
headers = auth_client.get_auth_headers()

# To swap to Basic Auth:
auth_client = AuthFactory.get_auth("basic", username="user", password="pwd")
headers = auth_client.get_auth_headers()
